   <font class="ArticleSource"><big>News Roundup:</big></font>
   <font class="ArticleHead"><big>Fear and Loathing</big></font>
   <font class="ArticleAuthorLight">&nbsp;filed by </font><font class="ArticleAuthor">Csenicier</font>
   <div align="right">
   <font class="ArticleTime">05/23/2002 04:04 PM CDT &nbsp;&nbsp; 3 Comments</font>
   <div align="left">
   <font class="ArticleText"><BIG>Gettin' Scooped</BIG><p><a href="http://eq.castersrealm.com/">Caster's Realm</a> has a nice <a href="http://eq.castersrealm.com/viewarticle.asp?Article=4305">interview</a> with Game Designer Shawn Lord.  Allow me to cut-n-paste a few highlights...<p><b>One of the great things about Planes of Power is that it will once again bring back the ability to form pick-up groups and 6 person groups and still be able to engage in raid level encounters...while there will still be encounters tailored to the current system of en-masse or large guild raids, we are trying hard to make the new high level content as accessible to players as we can.</b><p>Hmmm...  Sounds familiar.  If you remember, Luclin was similarly advertised, and certainly fell short of this goal.  Luclin wasn't any more tailored to pick-up-groups than any other expansion.<p><b>Timesinks will not be as bad as they were in the Luclin expansion.</b><p>Blessed be.  The thinking is that access to various planes will be granted through different avenues such as quests and uber-mobs and such.  The timesinks required to access keyed zones in Luclin is one of the expansion's greatest shortcomings.  It's good to see that the PoP zone designers are aware of this problem.<p>They're also trying to put in the concept of a Graveyard to aid in corpse recovery.  If your corpse is rotting on a particularly nasty plane, after some preset time it'll get warped to the Graveyard where you can rez and loot.<p>Also discussed, but not demonstrated, was the new particle spell effect system.  This will be the sole technical advancement to to introduced with PoP.<p><BIG>Balancing Act</BIG><p>Apparently casters, when ignored, don't get balanced all by themselves.  One such pesky caster <a href="http://boards.station.sony.com/ubb/everquest/Forum1/HTML/000582.html">grilled</a> Absor about promises made and not yet kept.<p><b>I assure you that the work on balancing continues, as does the work on the new interface and the bazaar. I'm not going to be able to give you any solid dates, but hopefully we'll have more for you on all these items soon(TM).<p>I have heard that the next steps in caster balance will be to finish up with pets, then probably move on to the priest classes for a bit.<p>Our desire is to do it properly, and for that we'll just need more time. All I can do is ask for your understanding and sympathize with your frustration. We all want this to be done so we can move on to the next thing, and the team is working very hard to make that happen.<br></b><p>I will take sympathy on poor Absor.  He doesn't turn the crank of the magic code machine at Verant, it's his job to take the heat when others aren't cranking - or something like that.  But time is about up on the bazaar, the new interface, and caster balancing (do they really need balancing?).<p>Rich Waters, Lead Designer for EverQuest, also <a href="http://pub23.ezboard.com/fgraffeswizardcompilationfrm1.showMessageRange?topicID=16679.topic&amp;start=41&amp;stop=60">weighs in</a> on the ongoing caster balancing saga.<p><b>Caster balancing isn't done, far from it in fact. We're very aware of it, and it's a priority of ours to finish. I understand that it's taking more time than players would like, and it's definately taking more time than I hoped to get it out to live servers.</b><p>Rich goes on to detail the holistic tight-rope that is caster balancing.<p><b>This gets more complex because no class has just one single ability. So, say (hypothetically) that we add a better heal to druids. Clerics are immediately concerned because druids are now healing better- what do clerics get? Wizards grow concerned because now not only can druids nuke pretty well, they also can heal even better than previously, making them a potentially better deal for a group or raid looking for members. No matter how small a change is, it causes ripples throughout the game, the player base, and all the community message boards. When it comes to class balancing, no change is really a small change.</b><p>It's reiterated by both Absor and Rich that this is a front-burner issue.  It's also interesting that the priest classes will be getting some long deserved love.<p><BIG>Staying Together by Slaying Together</BIG><p><a href="http://www.time.com/">Time.com</a> has a <a href="http://www.time.com/time/magazine/article/0,9171,1101020527-238612-1,00.html">new angle</a> on the <i>EverCrack ruined my family</i> article.  The bold author of this expose asserts the possibility that EQ may be family friendly.<p><b>In a fragmenting society that spends ever more time at home, EverQuest offers families a way of staying together by slaying together.<br>...<br>An unorthodox method of child rearing, to be sure, but hardly worse than parking the kids in front of the TV. &quot;It's not just watching cartoons,&quot; says EverQuest producer Rod Humble. &quot;It's an exercise of the mind.&quot;</b><p>Hats off to Chris Taylor for actually reporting both sides of this story.<p><BIG>Name that Retune</BIG><p>We reported awhile back on Thott's <a href="http://www.afterlifeguild.org/Thott/retune.php">watershed treatise</a> on the state of the Bard.  Absor recently (OK, not that recently, but likely still news to many - give us a break already) <a href="http://pub105.ezboard.com/ftheconcerthallbackstage.showMessageRange?topicID=13914.topic&amp;start=141&amp;stop=160">chimed in</a> over at the <a href="http://www.attcanada.net/~reaper/">Concert Hall</a>.<p><b><br>A bard can be in 'full nuke' mode at no cost, as far as downtime goes. The wizard can't do that and then fight the next fight without having to med up. This is one of the major strength of the manaless caster. It's the one thing that we, as game designers, have to keep in mind - no mana cost = no downtime, no risk of going OOM in a fight.<br></b><p>This statement, combined with previous statements that various Verant folks have made regarding their murky understanding of the class, leads one to conclude that Bards won't see much fine-tuning while other classes are getting 'balanced'.  I'm sure most Bards would settle for not being broken every other patch.<p><BIG>Honorable Mention</BIG><p>Congrats go out to the Magician's of Cazic-Thule who've <a href="http://pub6.ezboard.com/fthemagicianstowergeneral.showMessageRange?topicID=4974.topic&amp;start=1&amp;stop=20">unleashed their pets</a> upon the Plane of Air.<p>Verant corporate has a <a href="http://www.sonyonline.com/">revamped site</a> up and running.<p>New MMORPG announcements are frequent these days.  <a href="http://www.mystonline.com/">Myst Online</a> is diving into the fray as well as <a href="http://www.gamers.com/news/1159418">The Matrix online</a>.  Whoa.<br></font>
  </td>
 </tr>
